t 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">My name is Caroline Hodges and I am submitting this evidence as an individual concerned with cycling safety in London in particular and in the UK in general. I am a British citizen originally from the Wirral, and lived three years in London for my undergra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">duate studies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, between 2004 and 2008</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, during which time I cycled almost daily approx 25 minutes to university.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> I currently have many friends still living in London, many of whom cycle, and some of whom have stopped cycling in the past year due to safety co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ncerns.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> I have been resident in A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">msterdam, The Netherlands for the past year and a half where I cycle daily and consider my bike my primary means of transport within Amsterdam.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In my opinion the biggest obstacle to cycle safety in London and the UK is a la</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ck of segregated cycle lanes. In Holland, the vast majority of cycle lanes are physically segregated from the traffic, often as separate sections of the pavement rather than an allocated portion of the road. Larger roads always have a segregated bike lane,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or are otherwise </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">closed to cyclists (such as dual carriage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ways) and offer alternate routes. In central Amsterdam, smaller roads do not have cycle lanes but almost always</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have traffic calming measures.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> I have not lived in London since the cycle super highw</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ays were introduced but from what I have seen they are completely insufficient to promote cycle safety as they offer no segregation from the traffic and are hardly noticeable as they are not a solid colour.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In my view it is misguided to focus on traffic in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fractions by cyclists or helmet wearing. Whilst I do not dispute the benefit of wearing a helmet, and I did so in London, in Holland almost no-on wears a helmet and helmet-wearing is predominantly reserved for small children or those on racing bikes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> out of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> town. I </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">o not know, and have never seen someone wearing a helmet whilst using a bike for simple commuting from A to B.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cycling has immense health and environmental benefits, and is perfectly suited to small, crowded cities, such as London. Many people in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> London would cycle, if they perceived it to be safer. Segregated bike lanes would promote cycling and cycle safety immensely.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The more people that can be encouraged to cycle, the safer it becomes as motorists become more aware of cyclists on the road and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">negative at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">titudes towards cyclists change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and cycling becomes normalised. Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e government should introduce extensive measures to promote cycling, as a healthy, efficient and environmentally friendly means of transport.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_GoBack"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>